  "en_notes_yusuf": [
    {
      "note_no": "718",
      "note": "Sons of God: Cf. Job, 38:7: \"When the morning stars sang together, and all the sons of God shouted for joy.\" In the 29th Psalm, 1st verse, the authorised Translation \"O ye mighty\" should apparently be \"O ye sons of Elim\". El being a name of God. Cf. also Genesis, 6:2: \"The sons of God saw the daughters of men.\" Beloved: Cf. Psalms, 127:2: \"He giveth his beloved sleep.\" If used figuratively, these and like words refer to the love of Allah. Unfortunately, \"son\" used in a physical sense, or \"beloved\" in an exclusive sense as if Allah loved only the Jews, make a mockery of religion."
    },
    {
      "note_no": "719",
      "note": "This refrain in the last verse negatives the idea of sonship, and in this verse negatives the idea of an exclusive \"Beloved\". In both cases it means that Allah is independent of physical relationships or exclusive partiality."
    }
  ],
